<p>"<b>Big Bad John</b>" is a <a href="Country_music" title="Country music">country</a> song originally performed by <a href="Jimmy_Dean" title="Jimmy Dean">Jimmy Dean</a> and composed by Dean and <a href="Roy_Acuff" title="Roy Acuff">Roy Acuff</a>. Released in September 1961, by the beginning of November it went to number one on the <a href="Billboard_Hot_100" title="Billboard Hot 100">Billboard Hot 100</a> and won Dean the 1962 <a href="Grammy_Award_for_Best_Country_&_Western_Recording" title="Grammy Award for Best Country &amp; Western Recording">Grammy Award for Best Country &amp; Western Recording</a>. The song and its sequels tell a story typical of <a href="American_folklore" title="American folklore" class="mw-redirect">American folklore</a>, reminiscent of <a href="Paul_Bunyan" title="Paul Bunyan">Paul Bunyan</a> or <a href="John_Henry_(folklore)" title="John Henry (folklore)">John Henry</a>. <i>Big Bad John</i> was also the title of a 1990 <a href="Television_movie" title="Television movie" class="mw-redirect">television movie</a> starring Dean.</p>
<table id="toc" class="toc">
<tr>
